The '''Château Thorenc''' is a historic garden in [[Cannes]], France. It was established in 1870 for the [[Duke of Bedford|Duchess of Bedford]],<ref name="frenchministryinventaire">{{cite web|title=Inventaire général du patrimoine culturel: jardin d'agrément du château Thorenc|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=IA06000665|website=French Ministry of Culture|accessdate=July 7, 2017}}</ref> when a chateau was erected.<ref name="frenchministryinventairemaisonditechateau">{{cite web|title=Inventaire général du patrimoine culturel: maison dite Château Thorenc ou Château d'Oxford|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=IA06000292|website=French Ministry of Culture|accessdate=July 7, 2017}}</ref> It was acquired by Sir [[Richard Atwood Glass]] in 1876.<ref name="frenchministryinventairemaisonditechateau"/> It was subsequently purchased by the [[Duke of Montrose|Duchess of Montrose]], followed by [[Stuart Rendel, 1st Baron Rendel]].<ref name="frenchministryinventaire"/> It was purchased by Albert Neubauer in 1930.<ref name="frenchministryinventaire"/> He hired architects [[Louis Süe]] and [[Léon Le Bel]] to re-design the chateau, while painter [[Jean-Gabriel Domergue]] designed the Venetian living-room.<ref name="frenchministryinventairemaisonditechateau"/> It was owned by [[Bảo Đại]], the emperor of [[Annam (French protectorate)|Annam]], from 1937 to 1960.<ref name="frenchministryinventairemaisonditechateau"/> In 1968, the chateau was demolished and replaced with a residential building.<ref name="frenchministryinventairemaisonditechateau"/> Over the years, the garden designers were Mr Maria, followed by Lucien Lhotte, Denis Troncy and Jean-Baptiste Dental.<ref name="frenchministryinventaire"/>

