The '''Gambia Moral Congress''' (abbreviated '''GMC''') is a [[political party]] in [[the Gambia]]. The party was founded by the lawyer [[Mai Fatty|Mai Ahmad Fatty]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thepoint.gm/africa/gambia/article/lawyer-mai-fatty-forms-political-party |title=Lawyer Mai Fatty Forms Political Party |newspaper=[[The Point (the Gambia)|The Point]] |date=28 January 2009}}</ref> The motto of the party is ''People Power for Human Rights and Economic Justice''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://iec.gm/political-party/gambia-moral-congress-gmc/ |title=GMC registered party info |work=Independent Electoral Commission – The Gambia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://thegambiaecho.com/Homepage/tabid/36/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/1390/Default.aspx |title=The Gambia Moral Congress Maiden Speech of The National Executive Chairman, Barrister MAI N. K. FATTY, Esq. |newspaper=The Gambia Echo |date=28 January 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101223051843/http://thegambiaecho.com/Homepage/tabid/36/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/1390/Default.aspx |archivedate=23 December 2010}}</ref> The GMC was part of the [[Coalition 2016]] for the [[Gambian presidential election, 2016|2016 presidential election]], where [[Adama Barrow]] was declared the coalition's candidate and subsequently won.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gainako.com/gambian-opposition-parties-set-select-single-candidate-december-polls-convention/ |title=Gambian Opposition Parties Set to Select a Single Candidate for December polls at a Convention |website=GAINAKO |date=30 October 2016}}</ref> Mai Ahmad Fatty is the interior minister of the current government. He previously served as Barrow's personal adviser during the political impasse.

