The '''Gjermundbu helmet'''  is a [[Viking Age]] helmet.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://snl.no/Gjermundbu-funnet|title= Gjermundbu-funnet|publisher=Store norske leksikon |author= Frans-Arne Stylegar|accessdate= October  1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
|url =  http://nvg.org.au/article.php?story=20050923081703965&mode=print  |title=  Gjermundbu|publisher=   nvg.org.au||date=  September 22, 2005
|accessdate= October  1, 2017}}</ref>

The helmet was first discovered by accident during 1943 at the Gjermundbu farm near [[Haugsbygd]] in the municipality of [[Ringerike (municipality)|Ringerike]] in [[Buskerud]], Norway. Officials at the [[University of Oslo]] were later notified.  Conservator [[Sverre Marstrander]] and museum assistant [[Charlotte Blindheim]] led an investigation  which confirmed the existence of a burial chamber of historic value dating from the [[Viking era]]. The Gjermundbu finds (''Gjermundbu-funnet'') contained many artifacts including  articles of weaponry. The Gjermundbu  helmet was found in nine fragments and was subsequently restored. The helmet was made of iron and was in the shape of a peaked cap made from four plates. It is now on display at the [[Museum of Cultural History, Oslo|Museum of Cultural History]] of the [[University of Oslo]].<ref>{{cite web|url =  http://www.dokpro.uio.no/cgi-bin/stad/matr50|title=  Gjermbu. Norderhov herad. Buskerud|publisher=  Matrikkelutkastet av 1950|accessdate= October  1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =   http://no.unionpedia.org/c/Gjermundbu/vs/Liste_over_g%C3%A5rder_i_Ringerike|title=  Gjermundbu og Liste over gårder i Ringerike|publisher=  Unionpedia|accessdate= October  1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=   https://snl.no/Sverre_Marstrander|title= Sverre Marstrander|publisher=Store norske leksikon |author= Frans-Arne Stylegar|accessdate= October  1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =    http://no.unionpedia.org/Charlotte_Blindheim|title=  Charlotte Blindheim|publisher=  Unionpedia|accessdate= October  1, 2017}}</ref>

Together with the [[Tjele helmet fragment]], two fragments from [[Gotland]], and one fragment from [[Kiev]], it is the only known Viking helmet capable of reconstruction.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.thevintagenews.com/2016/12/22/the-only-surviving-example-of-a-complete-viking-helmet-in-existence-2/|title= The only surviving example of a complete Viking helmet in existence|publisher=   thevintagenews.com |author=  Ian Harvey
|date= December 22, 2016|accessdate= October  1, 2017}}</ref>

