{{Infobox hospital | name = Kamuzu Central Hospital'''Kamuzu Central Hospital''' | org/group = | logo = | logo_size = | image = | image_size = 225 | alt = | caption = | coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline, title}} --> | location = [[Lilongwe]], [[Malawi]] | region = | state = | country = | healthcare = <!-- UK: NHS; AU/CA: Medicare; ELSE free-form text, e.g. Private --> | funding = | type = | affiliation = [[University of North Carolina]] | patron = | network = Malawi German Networking for Capacity Building in Treatment, Training and Research at Kamuzu Central Hospital | standards = | emergency = Yes | beds = 9Est) 600-1,000 | speciality = | helipad = No | h1-number = | h1-length-f = | h1-length-m = | h1-surface = <!-- up to h12 --> | founded = <!-- cite in article as well --> | closed = | demolished = | website = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} --> | other_links = | module = }}
'''Kamuzu Central Hospital''' is a teritary referral hospital in the [[Lilongwe]], [[Malawi]]. It is estimated to have 600-1,000 beds, though the true number of patients always exceeds the number of beds. It serves approximately 5 million people. It has a partnership with the [[University of North Carolina]] in and Baylor College of Medicine/Texas Children's Hospital in the [[United States]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.med.unc.edu/surgery/world/malawi|title=Malawi — Department of Surgery - UNC School of Medicine|accessdate=6 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bipai.org/|title=BIPAI {{!}}|website=bipai.org|language=en|access-date=2017-11-17}}</ref> and a partnership project, called MAGNET <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esther-magnet.org|title=Hospital Partnership ESTHER-MAGNET|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> (Malawi German Networking for Capacity Building in Treatment, Training and Research at Kamuzu Central Hospital), with the Institute of Public Health <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.klinikum.uni-heidelberg.de/Hospital-Partnerships.5487.0.html|title=Disease Control in Disadvantaged Populations - Hospital Partnerships|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> of the [[University Hospital Heidelberg]] in [[Germany]], the [[University of Cologne|University Hospital Cologne]] and the [[University Hospital Bonn]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/272165912_Self-directed_e-learning_at_a_tertiary_hospital_in_Malawi__A_qualitative_Evaluation_and_Lessons_learnt|title=Self-directed e-learning at a tertiary hospital in Malawi – A qualitative Evaluation and Lessons learnt|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/273832159_Hospital_Partnership_MAGNET_Malawi_German_Networking_for_Capacity_Building_in_Treatment_Training_and_Research_at_Kamuzu_Central_Hospital_%28KCH%29_Lilongwe_Malawi|title=Hospital Partnership MAGNET: Malawi German Networking for Capacity Building in Treatment, Training and Research at Kamuzu Central Hospital (KCH), Lilongwe, Malawi|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref>
In 2012, President [[Bingu wa Mutharika]] was admitted to Kamuzu Central Hospital and was diagnosed with [[cardiac arrest]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2012/04/201245175737562122.html|title=Malawi president 'in critical condition|date=April 5, 2012|work=[[Al Jazeera English]]|accessdate=6 April 2012}}</ref>
==See also== * [[List of hospitals in Malawi]]
